               <msContents>
                  <summary> A complete copy of Book Five of the <title>Mas̲navī-i Ma‘navī</title>
                     (Spiritual Couplets) by <persName xml:lang="fa-Latn-x-lc" type="standard">Jalāl
                        al-Dīn Rūmī (1207–1273)</persName>, the fourth of a six-volume set together
                     with <ref target="https://www.fihrist.org.uk/catalog/manuscript_6736"
                           ><idno>Persian MS 250</idno></ref>, <ref
                        target="https://www.fihrist.org.uk/catalog/manuscript_6737"> 251</ref>, <ref
                        target="https://www.fihrist.org.uk/catalog/manuscript_6738">252</ref>, <ref
                        target="https://www.fihrist.org.uk/catalog/manuscript_6739">253</ref>, and
                        <ref target="https://www.fihrist.org.uk/catalog/manuscript_6741"
                           ><idno>255</idno></ref>. Since the set bears dedications to Prince Muḥammad Mu‘aẓẓam Bahādur Shāh, son of the Mughal Emperor ‘Ālamgīr I, who later succeeded him as <persName role="dte" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/314901452" key="person_314901452">Shāh ‘Ālam Bahādur I (r. 1707–1712)</persName>, he likely commissioned it.</summary>
                  <msItem xml:id="Persian_MS_254-item1">
                     <author ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/98930150" key="person_98930150">
                        <persName xml:lang="fa-Latn-x-lc" type="standard">Jalāl al-Dīn
                           Rūmī</persName>
                        <persName xml:lang="fa">جلال الدین رومی</persName>
                     </author>
                     <editor role="scr"><persName xml:lang="fa-Latn-x-lc" role="scr">Sīrāj al-Dīn
                           ibn Sayyid Bāyāzīd Kūrahvī Rūdawlī</persName>
                        <persName xml:lang="fa" type="alt"> سراج الدین بن سید بایازید گورهوی
                           رودولی</persName></editor>
                     <title xml:lang="fa-Latn-x-lc" key="work_20506" change="#ids-cleanup"
                        >Mas̲navī-i Ma‘navī</title>
                     <title xml:lang="fa" key="work_20506" change="#ids-cleanup"> مثنوی
                        معنوی</title>
                     <incipit xml:lang="ar" type="basmallah"><locus from="1b" to="1b"> برگ ۱پ (folio 1b):</locus>
                        بدانید و آگاه باشید که شریعت همچو شمعیت ره نیماید با انک
                        شمع بدست آوری راه رفته و کار کرده نشود چون در داه آمدی رفتن تو طریق است. </incipit>
                     <explicit xml:lang="fa">
                        <locus from="68b" to="68b"> برگ ۶۸پ (folio 68b):
                        </locus> زان نشد فاروق را زهری گزند * که بد آن تریاق فاروقیش قند </explicit>
                     <colophon xml:lang="fa">
                        <locus from="68b" to="68b"> برگ ۶۸پ (folio 68b):
                        </locus> تمام شد دفتر پنجم از مثنوی معنوی بحسن توفیقی الله تعالی بخط المذنب
                        خوریم الطلبه سراج الدین کورهوی معموله پرگنه رودولی فی منصاعف صوبه اوده سرکار
                        لکهنو. </colophon>
                     <colophon>Completed by <persName role="scr" key="person_f6555">Sirāj al-Dīn ibn
                           Bāyāzīd Kūrahvī Rūdawlī</persName>, probably in <settlement type="city"
                           ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/283512634">Calcutta (Kolkata)</settlement>
                        where he completed other volumes in the set, between circa <date
                           calendar="#Hijri-qamari" when="1694-12-28">38th and 40th years of the
                           Mughal Emperor ‘Ālamgīr's reign, hence 1106–08 AH, or 1694–98
                        CE)</date></colophon>
                     <note>The volume opens with a brief ornate rhyming prose preface, while the
                        poem proper commences on the lower half of the margin. The volume ends in
                        the lower margin of folio <locus from="68b" to="68b">68b</locus>.</note>
                     <textLang mainLang="fa">Persian</textLang>
                  </msItem>
               </msContents>
               <physDesc>
                  <objectDesc form="codex">
                     <supportDesc material="chart">
                        <support> Texblock comprised of cream-coloured <material>paper</material>
                           mixed with folios tinted a salmon pink hue, probably handmade in <country
                              cert="high" ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7000208">India</country>, with 9 laid lines
                           per cm and no discernible chain lines. </support>
                        <extent>
                           <measure unit="folios" quantity="68">68 folios (ff. iii + 68 +
                              iii)</measure>
                           <dimensions type="leaf" unit="mm">
                              <height>264</height>
                              <width>155</width>
                           </dimensions>
                           <dimensions type="written" unit="mm">
                              <height>205</height>
                              <width>110</width>
                           </dimensions>
                        </extent>
                        <foliation>
                           <p>Foliation marked at top-right corners of the a sides in pencilled
                              Arabic numerals by the cataloguer.</p>
                        </foliation>
                        <collation>Primarily quaternions thoughout. 1IV(16)1II(20)6IV(68).
                              <catchwords>Catchwords written at the lower-left margin by the gutter,
                              or lower-left corners on the b sides
                           throughout.</catchwords></collation>
                        <condition>In fair condition, with extensive water and insect damage with
                           many subsequent historical repairs throughout the volume. Folios <locus
                              from="28b" to="29a">28–29</locus>Small cut-out on <locus from="1"
                              to="1">1</locus> likely to remove the names of former owner <persName
                              role="fmo" cert="high" key="person_44733962"
                              ref="https://viaf.org/viaf/44733962/">Sir Gore Ouseley
                              (1770–1844)</persName>, with the name of another owner, Bengal indigo
                           merchant <persName role="fmo" key="person_f6562">John Harvey Danby (d. ca. 1830)</persName>
                           blacked out at top on <locus from="1b" to="1b">1b</locus>.</condition>
                     </supportDesc>
                     <layoutDesc>
                        <layout columns="1 2" ruledLines="64" n="mistara">Written in 1 to 2 columns,
                           in a two-part format starting with 19 lines in the centre then proceeding
                           to the margin. </layout>
                     </layoutDesc>
                  </objectDesc>
                  <handDesc>
                     <handNote scope="major" script="nastaliq" medium="ink">Written primarily in
                        nasta‘līq script in <material>black</material>, with subheaders in
                           <material>red</material>, by <persName role="scr">Sirāj al-Dīn ibn
                           Bāyāzīd Kūrahvī Rudawlī.</persName>. </handNote>
                  </handDesc>
                  <additions>
                     <label> Inscriptions: </label>
                     <list>
                        <item> The <locus from="iiib" to="iiib">third right flyleaf b side (f.
                              iiib)</locus> inscribed <q xml:lang="en">No. 84 Vol. 5</q> at top,
                           most probably in the hand of <persName role="fmo" cert="high"
                              key="person_44733962" ref="https://viaf.org/viaf/44733962/">Sir Gore
                              Ouseley (1770–1844)</persName>, that despite a subsequent owner
                           cutting out his signature, nevertheless matches his inscriptions in other
                           manuscripts, and further confirmed by a pencilled notation in another
                           hand (probably subsequent owner <persName cert="high" role="fmo"
                              type="standard" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/20108923/"
                              key="person_20108923">Nathaniel Bland (1803-1865)</persName>) in the
                           first volume of the set, <ref
                              target="https://www.fihrist.org.uk/catalog/manuscript_6736"
                                 ><idno>Persian MS 250</idno></ref>. </item>
                     </list>
                     <label>Bookplates:</label>
                     <list>
                        <item>
                           <locus from="left_paste-down"> left paste-down,</locus>
                           <q xml:lang="en">Bibliotheca Lindesiana</q> with shelfmark <q
                              xml:lang="en">2/G</q>, and <q xml:lang="en">Bland MSS No. 474</q>.
                        </item>
                     </list>
                  </additions>
                  <bindingDesc>
                     <binding notBefore="1694-12-28" notAfter="1850">
                        <p>Textblock repaired and resewn after suffering significant water and
                           insect damage, at two unsupported stations. Edges trimmed and coloured
                              <material>yellow</material>. Twined chevron endbands worked at head
                           and tail in <material>silver</material> and possibly <material
                              cert="medium">indigo</material>
                           <material>silk</material> threads, with the one at the head largely
                           abraded. Rebound with very thin <material>pasteboards</material>in full,
                           tight-backed smooth goatskin <material>leather</material>, originally
                           maroon-coloured but due to prolonged exposure to moisture now appears a
                           mottled medium-brown, but the original hue remains evident on the
                           turn-ins. Internal doublures of the same goatskin
                              <material>leather</material>, with the excess width put down as hinges
                           attached to the first and last flyleaves, with a strip of paper adhered
                           over top to disguise the join. Retains the original flyleaves of
                           thin-weight, cream-coloured, flocked <material>paper</material> probably
                           handmade in <country cert="high" ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7000208"
                              >India</country>, with ~8 laid lines per cm and few discernible chain
                           lines. Hinges of ivoury-coloured, medium-weight, sturdy
                              <material>paper</material>, also probably handmade in <country
                              cert="high" ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7000208">India</country>, the
                           same stock as the later flyleaves added to the other volumes in the set.
                              <material>Paper</material> label adhered to spine bears the Arabic
                           letter yā (ي), with the volume number written in Persian on the <locus
                              from="right_board" to="right_board">right board exterior</locus> in
                              <material>gold ink</material> in nasta‘līq script.</p>
                        <decoNote type="binding">
                           <p>Boards uniformly decorated together with the other volumes as a set,
                              with recessed <material>gilt paper</material> onlays for the central
                              scalloped mandorlas and detached pendants, but no onlays
                           remain.</p></decoNote>
                        <p><dimensions type="binding" unit="mm">
                              <height>266</height>
                              <width>161</width>
                              <depth>17</depth>
                           </dimensions>
                        </p>
                        <condition>Handle with caution. In poor condition, with the textblock
                           pulling away from the binding. The exterior suffers from extensive
                           staining, after exposure to prolonged moisture, especially at the spine
                           and tail edge. Upper grain layer delaminated in areas. The moisture
                           caused the interior pasteboards to swell and delaminate internally, which
                           resulted in the boards bulging, hence they now feel soft and
                           flexible.</condition>
                     </binding>
                  </bindingDesc>
               </physDesc>
               <history>
                  <origin>
                     <origPlace><placeName><settlement type="city"
                              ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/283512634">Calcutta (Kolkata)</settlement>,
                              <country ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7000208"
                           >India</country></placeName></origPlace>
                     <origDate calendar="Hijri-qamari" when="1697-03-01">9 Ẕī-l-Ḥijjah, 40th regnal
                        year (of the Mughal Emperor ‘Ālamgīr, hence 1108 AH, 29 June 1697
                        CE)</origDate></origin>
                  <provenance>
                     <p> Previously owned by one <persName xml:lang="fa-Latn-x-lc" role="fmo" key="person_f6556"
                           >Faz̤l Allāh Shāh Muḥammad</persName> as per his seal impression on folio
                           <locus from="1a" to="1a">1a</locus> in <ref
                           target="https://www.fihrist.org.uk/catalog/manuscript_6736"><idno>Persian
                              MS 250</idno></ref>, the first volume of the set. </p>
                  </provenance>
                  <provenance><p>Subsequently acquired, likely in <country cert="high"
                           ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7000208">India</country>, by indigo merchant
                     <persName role="fmo" key="person_f6562">Jonathan Harvey Danby (1767–1830)</persName>, of
                              <placeName><settlement type="town"
                              ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/125556231">Honiton</settlement>, <settlement
                              type="county" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/137143608"
                           >Devon</settlement></placeName>, who constructed a large factory in
                              <placeName><settlement type="town"
                              ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/14154074372611740681"
                           >Shikarpur</settlement>, <settlement type="district"
                              ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/125512807">Nadia District</settlement> in
                           what is now <settlement ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/133624114">West
                              Bengal</settlement></placeName> in circa <date calendar="#Gregorian"
                           notBefore="1790" notAfter="1795">1790 to 1795</date> (this firm later
                        evolved into Messrs. <orgName>Robert Watson &amp; Co.</orgName>, (this firm
                        later evolved into Messrs. <orgName>Robert Watson &amp; Co.</orgName>, the
                        preeminent <date calendar="#Gregorian" from="1837-06-20" to="1901-01-22"
                           >Victorian-era</date> subcontinental dyeworks), as per his name imprinted
                        at the top of folio <locus from="1b" to="1b">1b</locus>, albeit blacked out
                        by a later owner.</p></provenance>
                  <provenance><p> Later obtained by <persName cert="high" key="person_44733962"
                           ref="https://viaf.org/viaf/44733962/">Sir Gore Ouseley
                           (1770–1844)</persName> as per an unsigned inscription identifying his
                        hand on folio <locus from="vb" to="vb"> the fifth right flyleaf b side (f.
                           vb)</locus> of <ref
                           target="https://www.fihrist.org.uk/catalog/manuscript_6736"><idno>Persian
                              MS 250</idno></ref>.</p>
                  </provenance>
                  <provenance><p> Subsequently acquired by Persian scholar <persName type="standard"
                           role="fmo" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/20108923/" key="person_20108923"
                           >Nathaniel Bland (1803–1865)</persName>, after whose death <placeName ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7011781" key="place_7011781">London</placeName>
                        antiquarian dealer <persName type="standard" role="bsl"
                           ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/5679225/" key="person_5679225">Bernard Quaritch
                           (1819–1899)</persName> sold his oriental manuscripts to <persName
                           type="standard" role="fmo" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/97751058/"
                           key="person_97751058">Alexander Lindsay, 25th Earl of Crawford
                           (1812–1880)</persName> in <date calendar="#Gregorian" when="1866"
                           >1866</date>.</p>
                  </provenance>
                  <provenance>
                     <p>Purchased by <persName type="standard" role="dnr" key="person_f6379"
                           >Enriqueta Rylands (1843–1908)</persName> in <date calendar="#Gregorian"
                           when="1901">1901</date> from <persName type="standard" role="fmo"
                           ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/9985420/" key="person_9985420">James Ludovic
                           Lindsay, 26th Earl of Crawford (1847–1913)</persName>.</p>
                  </provenance>
                  <acquisition>
                     <p>Bequeathed by <persName type="standard" role="dnr" key="person_f6379"
                           >Enriqueta Rylands (1843–1908)</persName> in <date calendar="#Gregorian"
                           when="1908">1908</date> to the <orgName type="corporation" role="rps"
                           ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/312795145/">John Rylands
                        Library</orgName>.</p>
                  </acquisition>
               </history>
